ctices of the least-studied—and a difficult to study—segment of the Western Buddhist community, Buddhist sympathizers and solo practitioners. The book looks at the concerns of these correspondents, which included questions on meditation, dealing with isolation as a Buddhist, finding teachers and disillusion with teachers, and being a Buddhist in prison, among a myriad of other matters. The writers' letters reveal much about their notion of Zen and their image of a "Zen master." Coverage of Aitken's responses provides insight into the accommodation of solo practitioners and into the development of a particular strain of American Buddhism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aZen BuddhistszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aReligion and Spirituality : American Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Zen Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Zen (see also PHILOSOPHY / Zen).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844379940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438443799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438443799/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles